1 Introduction:

This R markdown file would be used to do statistical analysis for trailmaking test. It contains two main parts. In the first part, this file presents R code used to clean dataset. In the second part, this file presents some summary tables according to different regression models.

2 Apple Watch Data and GAPCare II Dataset - Baseline

After we have cleaned apple watch data of trailmaking, we need to choose the Baseline data. There is a csv file recording the relationship between the GAPCare II dataset and apple watch data and also recording the 30-days-followup, 60-days-followup, 90-days-followup, and baseline timelines. Here, we only care about baseline dataset.

3 Trailmaking Test

In this section, we focus on specific data needed for trailmaking test.

3.1 Trailmaking Test

The Trailmaking test administered in GAPcareII, alternating numbers and letters, measures executive function [refs]. The outcome measure for the trailmaking test is the time to completion. The format of the cleaned iWatch data for the trailmaking test are presented in figure below. It presents the processed data obtained directly from Redcap, and presents the analytic dataset derived from the processed data. The data description for both data files is discussed below. Each participant-trial has multiple rows associated with their tests. The first column pt is used for the participant trial identifier and study visit. This identifier can be linked to study ID by [insert procedure]. The second column Timestamp corresponds to the time in seconds [confirm units] where the participant logged either a correct or incorrect response (as indicated by the fourth column, 0 for correct, 1 for incorrect). The total number of errors the participant made in their test is presented in the fifth column. The third column, Index, represents the current guess as ordered by the “true” response order. Index ranges from 0 to 12, for a total of 13 correct responses needed to complete the test. When Index is 12 and Incorrect is 0, then the test is successfully completed. The outcome, time to completion, is then the corresponding Timestamp. The processed trailmaking test data are checked for completeness (i.e. all participants have a “successful” test) and manipulated to an analytic format which contains one row per participant- visit, reporting the time to completion in the third column (time), as well as the total number of errors the participant made during their test (second column, n err).

#Trailmaking Analysis

Baseline_trail<- Baseline_trail %>%

4 Covariates

Before doing regression analysis, we need to consider the confounders used in regression model. Let \(Age_{ij}\) , \(Male_i\), \(Education_i\), \(Assistive Device_{ij}\) , \(Fall History_i\), \(Head Strike_i\), and \(Cognitive Impairment_i\) similarly denote a participant’s age, indicator for gender male, education in years, use of an assistive device for walking, indicator for fall history at initial ED visit, head strike associated with presenting fall, and cognitive impairment as measured by answering three or more of the six item screener questions incorrectly, respectively. We created and cleaned these confounders in R:

#Filter Age, Gender, EDU, Cognitive Impairment, Head Strike, Fall History, and Assistive Devices
GAPCare_Data_trail <- GAPCare2 %>% filter(Event.Name == 'ED Visit ') #Filter ED Visit
for (i in 1:length(Baseline_trail$pt)){

                            %>% filter(Record.ID

                                             == Baseline_trail$ID[i]))$What.is.the.highest.grade.or.year.of.school.you.completed.

5 Regression Models

5.1 Balance and Outliers

Before doing regression analysis, we need to delete any outlier in response variable and balance all explanatory variables. After drawing the histogram of Timestamp, we found there is a value which is nearly 500 and larger a lot than other Timestamp values. Therefore, we think this is an accident and the outlier should be deleted. The reason why this patient(1168; 5967235711500288) took so long time I guessed is that the patient was 95 and he had to use lots of time to judge the distance between two numbers. The number of incorrects for this patient is only 6 which proves he had tried his best to connect each number correctly only once.

On the other hand, the distribution of Timestamp has a heavy tail. Hence, I will use negative binomial regression model (glm.nb in R) to do the analysis.

The plots of distribution:

hist(Baseline_trail$Timestamp, main="Histogram1")

Now, let’s consider the balance of explanatory variables. After checking all variables, I found variable education has an incorrect value “Do not know” and variable Fall has an incorrect value “Don’t Know”. The patients of the two incorrect values should not be involved in further analysis. On the other hand, the six item screener questions should be combined into one variable. If the value of one screener is ‘yes’, we rewrite it as 1. If the value of one screener is ‘no’, we rewrite it as 0. Then, sum all 1s and 0s together to get the variable sis. The code is shown below:

Baseline_trail <- filter(Baseline_trail, Timestamp < 400)
Baseline_trail <- filter(Baseline_trail, Education != "Do not know")
Baseline_trail <- filter(Baseline_trail, Fall != "Don't Know")

sis <- rep(0,length(Baseline_trail$pt))
for (i in 1:length(Baseline_trail$Age)){
  if (Baseline_trail$sis_1a[i] == "Yes"){
    sis[i] = sis[i] + 1
  }
  if (Baseline_trail$sis_2a[i] == "Yes"){
    sis[i] = sis[i] + 1
  }
  if (Baseline_trail$sis_3a[i] == "Yes"){
    sis[i] = sis[i] + 1
  }
  if (Baseline_trail$sis_1b[i] == "Yes"){
    sis[i] = sis[i] + 1
  }
  if (Baseline_trail$sis_2b[i] == "Yes"){
    sis[i] = sis[i] + 1
  }
  if (Baseline_trail$sis_3b[i] == "Yes"){
    sis[i] = sis[i] + 1
  }
  if (Baseline_trail$sis_4[i] == "Yes"){
    sis[i] = sis[i] + 1
  }
  if (Baseline_trail$sis_5[i] == "Yes"){
    sis[i] = sis[i] + 1
  }
  if (Baseline_trail$sis_6[i] == "Yes"){
    sis[i] = sis[i] + 1
  }
}
Baseline_trail$sis <- sis

5.2 Preprocessing of Categorical and Counting Variables

Before doing regression analysis, we still need to consider preprocessing categorical and counting variables. Since there is only one categorical variable sis, we do not consider any preprocess for it such as Minimax. However, for categorical variables, we create dummy variables for each one. The code for creating dummy variables for categorical variables is shown below:

#Preprocessing for categorical variables and counting variables
Gender_1 <- factor(Baseline_trail$Gender)
dummy_Gender <- model.matrix(~ Gender_1 - 1)
Baseline_trail$dummy_Gender <- dummy_Gender

Edu_1 <- factor(Baseline_trail$Education)
dummy_Education <- model.matrix(~ Edu_1 - 1)
Baseline_trail$dummy_Education <- dummy_Education

Inter_1 <- factor(Baseline_trail$Intervention)
dummy_Intervention <- model.matrix(~ Inter_1 - 1)
Baseline_trail$dummy_Intervention <- dummy_Intervention

head_1 <- factor(Baseline_trail$head)
dummy_head <- model.matrix(~ head_1 - 1)
Baseline_trail$dummy_head <- dummy_head

Device_1 <- factor(Baseline_trail$Device)
dummy_Device <- model.matrix(~ Device_1 - 1)
Baseline_trail$dummy_Device <- dummy_Device

Fall_1 <- factor(Baseline_trail$Fall)
dummy_Fall <- model.matrix(~ Fall_1 - 1)
Baseline_trail$dummy_Fall <- dummy_Fall

5.3 Regression models for trailmaking test

Below contain all regression models:

\[E[TMT_{i1}]=\beta_0+\beta_1Age_{i1}+\beta_2Male_i+\beta_3Education_i\] \[E[TMT_{i1}]=\beta_0+\beta_1Assistive Device_{i1}+\beta_2Age_{i1}+\beta_2Male_i+\beta_2Education_i\]

\[E[TMT_{i1}]=\beta_0+\beta_1Cognitive Impairment_{i1}+\beta_2Age_{i1}+\beta_2Male_i+\beta_2Education_i\]

\[E[TMT_{i1}]=\beta_0+\beta_1Head Strike_{i1}+\beta_2Age_{i1}+\beta_2Male_i+\beta_2Education_i\]

\[E[TMT_{i1}]=\beta_0+\beta_1Fall History_{i1}+\beta_2Age_{i1}+\beta_2Male_i+\beta_2Education_i\]

#Regression models
model1_p <- glm.nb(Timestamp ~ Age + Gender + Education, data=Baseline_trail)
model2_p <- glm.nb(Timestamp ~ Age + Gender + Education + Device, data=Baseline_trail)
model3_p <- glm.nb(Timestamp ~ Age + Gender + Education + sis, data=Baseline_trail)
model4_p <- glm.nb(Timestamp ~ Age + Gender + Education + head, data=Baseline_trail)
model5_p <- glm.nb(Timestamp ~ Age + Gender + Education + Fall, data=Baseline_trail)

#Regression models
model1 <- glm.nb(Timestamp ~ Age + dummy_Gender + dummy_Education, data=Baseline_trail)
model2 <- glm.nb(Timestamp ~ Age + dummy_Gender + dummy_Education + dummy_Device, data=Baseline_trail)
model3 <- glm.nb(Timestamp ~ Age + dummy_Gender + dummy_Education + sis, data=Baseline_trail)
model4 <- glm.nb(Timestamp ~ Age + dummy_Gender + dummy_Education + dummy_head, data=Baseline_trail)
model5 <- glm.nb(Timestamp ~ Age + dummy_Gender + dummy_Education + dummy_Fall, data=Baseline_trail)

5.4 Check Assumptions for Regression Models

Even if we have built our models, we should check some assumptions for these models before using their outcomes. Firstly, we should check the collinearity and independence of explanatory variables. For collinearity, I used variance inflation factor to check. In general, the VIF should be near 1 and not to large. All VIFs in all five models are between 1.0 to 1.3 which are good enough. For the independence, I used Durbin–Watson statistic to check. In general, the Durbin–Watson statistic should be near 2. The Durbin–Watson statistic for five models are all 2 which are also good enough. Therefore, the assumptions of collinearity and independence are satisfied.

#Durbin-Watson
D1 <- durbinWatsonTest(model1)
D2 <- durbinWatsonTest(model2)
D3 <- durbinWatsonTest(model3)
D4 <- durbinWatsonTest(model4)
D5 <- durbinWatsonTest(model5)

#VIF Score
DD1 <- car::vif(model1_p)
DD2 <- car::vif(model2_p)
DD3 <- car::vif(model3_p)
DD4 <- car::vif(model4_p)
DD5 <- car::vif(model5_p)

Secondly, we should check the residual plots and qqplots for each model. In general, the residual line should follow the line \(y=0\) and the line in qqplot should follow \(y=x\). The plots for each model are shown below.

Residual plots:

par(mfrow=c(2,3))
plot(model1, which = 1, xlab("model1")) #Residual plot
plot(model2, which = 1, xlab("model2")) #Residual plot
plot(model3, which = 1, xlab("model3")) #Residual plot
plot(model4, which = 1, xlab("model4")) #Residual plot
plot(model5, which = 1, xlab("model5")) #Residual plot

Q-Q plots:

par(mfrow=c(2,3))
plot(model1, which = 2, xlab("model1")) #Normality plot
plot(model2, which = 2, xlab("model2")) #Normality plot
plot(model3, which = 2, xlab("model3")) #Normality plot
plot(model4, which = 2, xlab("model4")) #Normality plot
plot(model5, which = 2, xlab("model5")) #Normality plot
